<tr><td class=3D"h2">Note:</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
<!-- end Note -->

<p><b>  RULES FOR SIGNIFICANT FIGURES </b>
</p><p>1. <b>All non-zero numbers ARE significant.</b>  The number 33.2 has=
 THREE significant figures because all of the digits present are non-zero.
</p><p>2. <b>Zeros between two non-zero digits ARE significant.</b>  2051 h=
as FOUR significant figures.  The zero is between a 2 and a 5.
</p><p>3. <b>Leading zeros are NOT significant.</b>  They're nothing more t=
han "place holders."  The number 0.54 has only TWO significant figures.  0.=
0032 also has TWO significant figures.  All of the zeros are leading.
</p><p>4. <b>Trailing zeros to the right of the decimal ARE significant.</b=
>  There are FOUR significant figures in 92.00. =20
</p><p>92.00 is different from 92: a scientist who measures 92.00 millilite=
rs knows his value to the nearest 1/100th milliliter; meanwhile his colleag=
ue who measured 92 milliliters only knows his value to the nearest 1 millil=
iter.  It's important to understand that "zero" does not mean "nothing."  Z=
ero denotes actual information, just like any other number.  You cannot tag=
 on zeros that aren't certain to belong there.
</p><p>5. <b>Trailing zeros in a whole number with the decimal shown ARE si=
gnificant.</b>  Placing a decimal at the end of a number is usually not don=
e.  By convention, however, this decimal indicates a significant zero.  For=
 example, "540." indicates that the trailing zero IS significant; there are=
 THREE significant figures in this value.
</p><p>6. <b>Trailing zeros in a whole number with no decimal shown are NOT=
 significant.</b>  Writing just "540" indicates that the zero is NOT signif=
icant, and there are only TWO significant figures in this value.
</p><p>7. <b>Exact numbers have an INFINITE number of significant figures.<=
/b>  This rule applies to numbers that are definitions.  For example, 1 met=
er =3D 1.00 meters =3D 1.0000 meters =3D <br> 1.0000000000000000000 meters,=
 etc. =20
</p><p>So now back to the example posed in the <a class=3D"chapter5" target=
=3D"Text_Notebox" href=3D"https://ccnmtl.columbia.edu/projects/mmt/frontier=
s/web/chapter_5/6664.html" title=3D"Rounding">Rounding Tutorial</a>:
<i>Round 1000.3 to four significant figures.</i>
1000.3 has five significant figures (the zeros are between non-zero digits =
1 and 3, so by rule 2 above, they are significant.)  We need to drop the fi=
nal 3, and since 3 &lt; 5, we leave the last zero alone.  so 1000. is our f=
our-significant-figure answer.  (from rules 5 and 6, we see that in order f=
or the trailing zeros to "count" as significant, they must be followed by a=
 decimal.  Writing just "1000" would give us only one significant figure.)
</p><p>8. <b>For a number in scientific notation: N x 10<sup>x</sup>, all d=
igits comprising N ARE significant by the first 6 rules; "10" and "x" are N=
OT significant.</b>  5.02 x 10<sup>4</sup> has THREE significant figures: "=
5.02."  "10 and "4" are not significant.
</p><p>Rule 8 provides the opportunity to change the number of significant =
figures in a value by manipulating its form.  For example, let's try writin=
g 1100 with THREE significant figures.  By rule 6, 1100 has TWO significant=
 figures; its two trailing zeros are not significant.  If we add a decimal =
to the end, we have 1100., with FOUR significant figures (by rule 5.)  But =
by writing it in <a class=3D"chapter1" target=3D"Text_Notebox" href=3D"http=
s://ccnmtl.columbia.edu/projects/mmt/frontiers/web/chapter_1/6253.html" tit=
le=3D"Scientific Notation: Powers of Ten">scientific notation</a>: 1.10 x 1=
0<sup>3</sup>, we create a THREE-significant-figure value.
</p>



